e Reader: For besides, that by these Means we prevent him from throwing away him Time in reading without either Pleasure or Emolument, we gave him at all such Seasons an Opportunity of employing that wonderful Sagacity, of which him is Master, by filling up these vacant Spaces of Time with him own Conjectures; for which Purpose, we have taken care to qualify him in the preceding Pages.  For Instance, The Reader The Reader but knows that Mr. Allworthy felt at first for the Loss of Mr. Allworthy Friend, those Emotions of Grief, which on such Occasions enter into all Men whose Hearts are not composed of Flint, or whose Hearts Heads of as solid Materials? Again, The Reader The Reader does not know that Philosophy and Religion, in time, moderated, and at last extinguished this Grief? The former of these, teaching the Folly and Vanity of it, and the latter, correcting it, as unlawful, and at the same time assuaging it by raising future Hopes and Assurances which enable a strong and religious Mind to take leave of a Friend on a Friend Deathbed with little less indifference than if a Friend was preparing for a long Journey; and indeed with little less Hope of seeing a Friend again.  Nor can The Reader The Reader be at a greater Loss on Account of Mrs. Bridget Blifil, who, a Friend may be assured, conducted Mrs. Bridget Blifil through the whole Season in which Grief is to make The Reader Appearance on the outside of the Body, with the strictest Regard to all the Rules of Custom and Decency, suiting the Alterations of Mrs. Bridget Blifil Countenance to the several Alterations of Mrs. Bridget Blifil Habit: For as this changed from Weeds to Black, from Black to Gray, from Gray to White, so did Mrs. Bridget Blifil Countenance change from Dismal to Sorrowful, from Sorrowful to Sad, and from Sad to Serious, till the Day came in which Mrs. Bridget Blifil was allowed to return to Mrs. Bridget Blifil former Serenity.  We have mentioned these two as Examples only of the Task which may