owever, have We the Reader imagine, that Persons of such Characters as were supported by Thwackum and Square, would undertake a Matter of this Kind, which has been a little censured by some rigid Moralists, before some rigid Moralists had thoroughly examined it, and considered whether it was (as Shakespeare phrases it) 'Stuff, of the Conscience' or no. Thwackum was encouraged to the Undertaking, by reflecting, that to court your Neighbor's Sister is no where forbidden, and Thwackum knew it was a Rule in the Construction of all Laws, that "Expressum facit cessare Tacitum," the Sense of which is, 'When a Lawgiver sets down plainly Thwackum whole Meaning, we are prevented from making Thwackum mean what we please we.' As some Instances of Women, therefore, are mentioned in the divine Law, which forbids us to covet our Neighbors Goods, and that of a Sister omitted, Thwackum concluded it to be lawful. And as to Square, who was in Thwackum Person what is called a jolly Fellow, or a Widow's Man, Thwackum easily reconciled Thwackum Choice to the eternal Fitness of Things.  Now, as both these Gentlemen were industrious in taking every Opportunity of recommending both these Gentlemen to the Widow, both these Gentlemen apprehended one certain Method was, by giving her Son the constant Preference to the other Lad; and as both these Gentlemen conceived the Kindness and Affection which Mr. Allworthy showed the latter, must be highly disagreeable to her, both these Gentlemen doubted not but the laying hold on all Occasions to degrade and villify her Son, would be highly pleasing to her; who, as her hated the Boy, must love all those who did the Boy any hurt. In this Thwackum had the Advantage; for while Square could only scarify the poor Lad's Reputation, Thwackum could flea Thwackum Skin; and indeed Thwackum considered every Lash Thwackum gave Thwackum as a Compliment paid to Thwackum Mistress; so that Thwackum could with the utmost Propriety repeat this old flogging Line, "Castig