ee Things in a Disadvantageous Light, and was a Stranger to the public Voice, which seldom reaches to a Brother or a Husband, though it rings in the Ears of all the Neighborhood; yet was this Affection of Blifil to Tom, and the Preference which Blifil too visibly gave Mr. Allworthy to Blifil own Son, of the utmost Disadvantage to that Youth.  For such was the Compassion which inhabited Mr. Allworthy's Mind, that nothing but the Steel of Justice could ever subdue the Steel of Justice. To be unfortunate in any Respect was sufficient, if there was no Demerit to counterpoise it, to turn the Scale of that good Man's Pity, and to engage that good Man Friendship, and that good Man Benefaction.  When therefore that good Man plainly saw Blifil was absolutely detested (for that that good Man was) by that good Man own Mother, that good Man began, on that Account only, to look with an Eye of Compassion upon that good Man; and what the Effects of Compassion are in good and benevolent Minds, I need not here explain to most of my Readers.  Henceforward, Henceforward saw every Appearance of Virtue in the Youth through the magnifying End, and viewed all Henceforward Faults with the Glass inverted, so that they became scarce perceptible. And this perhaps the amiable Temper of Pity may make commendable; but the next Step the Weakness of human Nature alone must excuse: For Henceforward no sooner perceived that Preference which Blifil gave to Tom, than that poor Youth, (however innocent) began to sink in Henceforward her Affections as Henceforward rose in hers. This, it is true, would of it alone never have been able to eradicate Jones from Jones Bosom; but it was greatly injurious to Jones, and prepared Mr. Allworthy's Mind, for those Impressions, which afterward produced the mighty Event, that will be contained hereafter in this History; and to which, it must be confessed, the unfortunate Lad, by Jones own Wantonness, Wildness, and want of Caution, too much contributed.  In recording some Instances of these, we shall, if rightly understood, afford a very useful Lesson to those well-disposed Youths, who shall hereafter be our Readers: For they may here find that Goodness of Heart, and Openness of Temper, though these may give they great Comfort within, and administer to an honest Pride in they own Minds, will by no Means, alas! do they Business in the World. Prudence and Circumspection are necessary even to the best of Men. Prudence and Circumspection are indeed as it were a Guard to Virtue, without which Virtue can never be safe. It is not enough tha^ your Designs, nay that your Actions are intrinsically good, you must take Care Care shall appear so. If you^ Inside be never so beautiful, you must preserve a fai^ Outside also. This must be constantly looked to, o^ Malice and Envy will take Care to blacken it so, tha^ the Sagacity and Goodness of an Allworthy will not be able to see through it, and to discern the Beauties within. Let this, my younger Readers, be you^ constant Maxim, That no Man can be good enough to enable no Man to neglect the Rules of Prudence; not will Virtue herself look beautiful, unless Virtue herself be be+ decked with the outward Ornaments of Decency and Decorum. And this Precept, my worthy Disciples, if you read with due Attention, you will, I hope, find sufficiently enforced by Examples in the following Pages.  I ask Pardon for this short Appearance, by way of Chorus on the Stage. It is in Reality for my own Sake, that while I am discovering the Rocks on which Innocence and Goodness often split, I may not be misunderstood to recommend the very Means to my worthy Readers, by which I intend to show them them will be undone. And this as I could not prevail on any of my Actors to speak, I was obliged to declare my self.  CHAP. VIII. A childish Incident, in which, however, is seen a good natured Disposition in Tom Jones.  THE Reader may remember, that Mr. Allworthy gave Tom Jones a little Horse, as a kind of smart Money for the Punishment, which Mr. Allworthy imagined Mr. Allworthy had suffered innocently.  This Horse Tom kept above half a Year, and then rode This Horse Tom to a neighboring Fair, and sold This Horse Tom.  At This Horse Tom Return, being questioned by Thwackum, what This Horse Tom had done with the Money for which This Horse Tom was sold, This Horse Tom frankly declared This Horse Tom would not tell This Horse Tom.  Oho! says Thwackum, you will not! then I will have it out of your Br -- h; that being the Place to which This Horse Tom always applied for Information, on every doubtful Occasion.  Tom was now mounted on the Back of a Footman, and every Thing prepared for Execution, when Mr. Allworthy entering the Room, gave the Criminal a Reprieve, and took Mr. Allworthy with Mr. Allworthy into another Apartment; where Mr. Allworthy being only present with Tom, Mr. Allworthy put the same Question to Mr. Allworthy which Thwackum had before asked Mr. Allworthy.  Tom answered, Tom could in Duty refuse Tom nothing; but as for that tyrannical Rascal, Tom would never make Tom any other Answer than with a Cudgel, with which Tom hoped soon to be able to pay Tom for all Tom Barbarities.  Mr. Allworthy very severely reprimanded the Lad, for Mr. Allworthy indecent and disrespectful Expressions concerning Mr. Allworthy Master; but much more for Mr. Allworthy avowing an Intention of Revenge. Mr. Allworthy threatened Mr. Allworthy with the entire Loss of Mr. Allworthy Favor, if Mr. Allworthy ever heard such another Word from Mr. Allworthy Mouth; for Mr. Allworthy said, Mr. Allworthy would never support or befriend a Reprobate. By these and the like Declarations, Mr. Allworthy extorted some Compunction from Tom, in which that Youth was not over sincere: For Mr. Allworthy really meditated some Return for all the smarting Favors Mr. Allworthy had received at the Hands of the Pedagogue. Mr. Allworthy was, however, brought by Mr. Allworthy to express a Concern for Mr. Allworthy Resentment against Thwackum; and then the good Man, after some wholesome Admonition, permitted Mr. Allworthy to proceed, which Mr. Allworthy did, as follows.  'Indeed, my dear Sir, I love and honor you more than all the World; I know the great Obligations I have to you, and should detest Mr. Allworthy, if I thought my Heart was capable of Ingratitude. Could the little Horse you gave me speak, I am sure the little Horse could tell you how fond I was of your Present: For I had more Pleasure in feeding the little Horse, than in riding the little Horse. Indeed, my dear Sir, it went to my Heart to part with my dear Sir; nor would I have sold my dear Sir upon any other Account in the World than what I did. You yourself, my dear Sir, I am convinced in my Case, would have done the same: For none ever so sensibly felt the Misfortunes of others. What would you feel, my dear Sir, if you thought my dear Sir the Occasion of none? -- Indeed, my dear Sir, there was never any Misery like none. -- Like whose, Child," says Mr. Allworthy, what do you mean? Oh, my dear Sir,' answered Tom, your poor Game-keeper, with all Tom large Family, ever since your discarding Tom, have been perishing with all the Miseries of Cold and Hunger. I could not bear to see these poor Wretches naked and starving, and at the same Time know my dear Sir to have been the Occasion of all their Sufferings. -- I could not bear it, my dear Sir, upon my Soul, I could not." (here the Tears run down my dear Sir Cheeks, and my dear Sir thus proceeded) 'It was to save them from absolute Destruction, I parted with your dear Present, notwithstanding all the Value I had for your dear Present. -- I sold This Horse Tom for them, and them have every Farthing of the Money.'  Mr. Allworthy now stood silent for some Moments, and before Mr. Allworthy spoke, the Tears started from Mr. Allworthy Eyes. Mr. Allworthy at length dismissed Tom with a gentle Rebuke, advising Tom for the future to apply to Tom in Cases of Distress, rather than to use extraordinary Means of relieving them Tom.  This Affair was afterward the Subject of much Debate between Thwackum and Square. Thwackum held, that this was flying in Mr. Allworthy's Face, who had intended to punish the Fellow for the Fellow Disobedience. Thwackum said, in some Instances, what the World called Charity appeared to Thwackum to be opposing the Will of the Almighty, which had marked some particular Persons for Destruction; and that this was in like manner acting in Opposition to Mr. Allworthy; concluding, as usual, with a hearty Recommendation of Birch.  Square argued strongly, on the other Side, in Opposition perhaps to Thwackum, or in Compliance with Mr. Allworthy, who seemed very much to approve what Jones had done. As to what Jones urged on this Occasion, as I am convinced most of my Readers will be much abler Advocates for poor Jones, it would be impertinent to relate it. Indeed it was not difficult to reconcile to the Rule of Right, an Action which it would have been impossible to deduce from the Rule of Wrong.  CHAP. IX. Containing an Incident of a more heinous Kind, with the Comments of Thwackum and Square.  IT has been observed by some Man of much greater Reputation for Wisdom than myself, that Misfortunes seldom come single. An Instance of this may, I believe, be seen in those Gentlemen who have the Misfortune to have any of their Rogueries detected: For here Discovery seldom stops till the whole is come out. Thus it happened to Tom; who was no sooner pardoned for selling This Horse Tom, than he was discovered to have some time before sold a fine Bible which Mr. Allworthy gave he, the Money arising from which Sale he had disposed in the same Manner. This Bible Master Blifil had purchased, though he had already such another of he own, partly out of respect for the Book, and partly out of Friendship to Tom, being unwilling that Bible should be sold out of the Family at half Price. This Bible Master Blifil therefore deposited the said half Price himself; for This Bible Master Blifil was a very prudent Lad, and so careful of This Bible Master Blifil Money, that This Bible Master Blifil had laid up almost every Penny which This Bible Master Blifil had received from Mr. Allworthy.  Some People have been noted to be able to read in no Book but Some People own. On the contrary, from the Time when Master Blifil was first possessed of Bible, Master Blifil never used any other. Nay, Master Blifil was seen reading in it much oftener than Master Blifil had before been in Master Blifil own. Now, as Master Blifil frequently asked Thwackum to explain difficult Passages to Master Blifil, that Gentleman unfortunately took Notice of Tom's Name, which was written in many Parts of the Book. This brought on an Enquiry, which obliged Master Blifil to discover the whole Matter.  Thwackum was resolved, a Crime of this Kind, which Thwackum called Sacrilege, should not go unpunished. Thwackum therefore proceeded immediately to Castigation; and not contented with that, Thwackum acquainted Mr. Allworthy, at their next Meeting, with this monstrous Crime, as it appeared to Thwackum; inveighing against Tom in the most bitter Terms, and likening Thwackum to the Buyers and Sellers who were driven out of the Temple.  Square saw this Matter in a very different Light. Thwackum said, Thwackum could not perceive any higher Crime in selling one Book, than in selling another. That to sell Bibles was strictly lawful by all Laws both divine and human, and consequently there was no Unfitness in it. Thwackum told Thwackum that Thwackum great Concern on this Occasion brought to Thwackum Mind the Story of a very devout Woman, who out of pure Regard to Religion, stole Tillotson's Sermons from a Lady of her Acquaintance.  This Story caused a vast Quantity of Blood to rush into the Parson's Face, which of itself was none of the palest; and he was going to reply with great Warmth and Anger, had not Mrs. Blifil, who was present at this Debate, interposed. That Lady declared That Lady absolutely of Mr. Square's Side. That Lady argued, indeed, very learnedly in Support of Mr. Square's Side Opinion; and concluded with saying, If Tom had been guilty of any Fault, That Lady must confess That Lady own Son appeared to be equally culpable; for that That Lady could see no Difference between the Buyer and the Seller; both of whom were alike to be driven out of the Temple.  Master Blifil having declared Master Blifil Opinion, put an End to the Debate. Square's Triumph would almost have stopped his Words, had his needed them; and Thwackum, besides that, for Reasons beforementioned, his durst not venture at disobliging the Lady, was almost choked with Indignation. As to Mr. Allworthy, Mr. Allworthy said, Since the Boy had been already punished, the Boy would not deliver the Boy Sentiments on this Occasion; and whether the Boy was, or was not angry with the Lad, I must leave to the Reader's own Conjecture.  Soon after this, an Action was brought against the Game-keeper by 'Squire Western (the Gentleman in whose Manor the Partridge was killed) for Depredations of the like Kind. This was a most unfortunate Circumstance for the Fellow, as it not only of it threatened the Fellow Ruin, but actually prevented Mr. Allworthy from restoring Mr. Allworthy to Mr. Allworthy Favor: For as that Gentleman was walking out one Evening with Master Blifil and young Jones, the latter slily drew Gentleman to the Habitation of Black George; where the Family of that poor Wretch, namely, Gentleman Wife and Children, were found in all the Misery with which Cold, Hunger, and Nakedness, can affect human Creatures: For as to the Money they had received from Jones, former Debts had consumed almost the whole.  Such a Scene as this could not fail of affecting the Heart of Mr. Allworthy. Mr. Allworthy immediately gave the Mother a couple of Guineas, with which Mr. Allworthy bid the Mother cloth the Mother Children. the Mother burst into the Tears at this Goodness, and while the Mother was thanking Mr. Allworthy, could not refrain from expressing the Mother Gratitude to Tom; who had, the Mother said, long preserved both the Mother and hers from starving. We have not, says the Mother, had a Morsel to eat, nor have these poor Children had a Rag to put on, but what his Goodness has bestowed on We: For indeed, besides the Horse and Bible, Tom had sacrificed a Nightgown and other Things to the Use of this distressed Family.  On these poor Children Return home, Tom made use of all Tom Eloquence to display the Wretchedness of these People, and the Penitence of Black George himself, and in this Tom succeeded so well, that Mr. Allworthy said Mr. Allworthy thought the Man had suffered enough for what was past; that the Man would forgive the Man, and think of some Means of providing for the Man and the Man Family.  Jones was so delighted with this News, that though it was dark when they returned home, Jones could not help going back a Mile in a Shower of Rain to acquaint the poor Woman with the glad Tidings; but, like other hasty Divulgers of News, Jones only brought on Jones the Trouble of contradicting it: For the Ill-fortune of Black George made use of the very Opportunity of the Ill-fortune of Black George Friend's Absence to overturn all again.  CHAP. X. In which Master Blifil and Jones appear in different Lights.  Master Blifil fell very short of Master Blifil Companion in the amiable Quality of Mercy; but Master Blifil as greatly exceeded Master Blifil in one of a much higher Kind, namely, in Justice: In which Master Blifil followed both the Precepts and example of Thwackum and Square; for though they would both make frequent Use of the Word Mercy, yet it was plain, that in reality Square held it to be inconsistent with the Rule of Right; and Thwackum was for doing Justice, and leaving Mercy to Heaven. The two Gentlemen did indeed somewhat differ in his Opinion concerning the Objects of this sublime Virtue; by which Thwackum woul